24: This thesis presents an autonomous, multi-agent AI framework designed to rigorously validate phenomenological physics models. The framework is applied to evaluate a proposed multi-component model for transverse momentum ($p_T$) spectra produced in high-energy collisions. We definitively prove the intrinsic over-parameterization of the multi-component J\"uttner model, contrasting its failure to converge against robust Blast-Wave (BGBW) and Tsallis baselines. Furthermore, via comprehensive covariance extraction and profile-likelihood scanning, we document a severe $T_{\text{kin}}$--$\beta_s$ parameter degeneracy in the BGBW model, demonstrating that single-point parameter estimates understate true uncertainties. Ultimately, an automated model competition establishes the 2-component Tsallis distribution as the superior phenomenological descriptor for ATLAS 13 TeV $pp$ spectra.
